{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}} The '''Muldergate scandal''', also known as the '''Information Scandal''', was a [[South Africa]]n [[political scandal]] involving the Department of Information.<Ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/pages/library-resources/articles_papers/information-scandal.htm|title=The Information Scandal|publisher=South African History Online|accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref>
[[South African]] Prime Minister [[B. J. Vorster]], [[Connie Mulder|Dr. Connie Mulder]] (Minister of Information) and [[Eschel Rhoodie|Dr. Eschel Rhoodie]] (Secretary of the Department of Information) were implicated in plans to use government resources to fight a propaganda war for the then [[apartheid]] government. In 1973 John Vorster had agreed to Mulder's plan to shift about 64 million [[South African rand|rand]] from the defense budget to undertake a series of propaganda projects. Plans included bribes of international news agencies and the purchase of the ''[[Washington Star]]'' newspaper.
Vorster was also implicated in the use of a secret slush fund to establish ''[[The Citizen (South Africa)|The Citizen]]'', the only major English-language newspaper that was favourable to the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]].
A commission of inquiry concluded in mid-1979 that Vorster knew "everything" about the corruption and had tolerated it. He resigned from the [[State President of South Africa|presidency]] in disgrace.
